<case:headnote>
<case:info><case:casename searchtype="PRACTICE-NOTE">PETER KENT DEVELOPMENT PTY LTD v AUSTRALIA AND NEW ZEALAND BANKING GROUP LTD</case:casename></case:info>
<case:info>
<case:courtinfo><case:courtname>Supreme Court NSW</case:courtname>
<case:judges><case:judge>Hunt J</case:judge>
</case:judges><case:dates><case:decisiondate>6 May 1980</case:decisiondate></case:dates>
<case:filenum>CL No 16824/79</case:filenum>
</case:courtinfo></case:info><catchwordgrp><catchwords><catchphrase>UCPR r 13.4 &#x2014; [SCR Pt 13 r 5]</catchphrase><catchphrase>Summary disposal</catchphrase></catchwords>
</catchwordgrp></case:headnote><case:content>
<case:judgments><case:judgment><case:courtinfo><case:judges><case:judge>Hunt J</case:judge></case:judges></case:courtinfo>
<case:judgmentbody>
<p>
<text>[His Honour dealt with matters not germane to this report and continued:] Part 13 r 2 permits summary judgment to be directed in favour of a <emph typestyle="it">plaintiff</emph> where there is evidence of the facts on which the claim is based and where it is sworn by the plaintiff that in his belief the defendant has no defence to that claim. The issue which must then be decided is whether there is a real issue of fact to be investigated such as to give the defendant a defence on the merits.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Part 13 r 5 permits the grant of a stay of proceedings or summary judgment to be directed for the <emph typestyle="it">defendant</emph> where no reasonable cause of action is disclosed or where the proceedings are frivolous or vexatious or an abuse of the process of the court.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Part 15 r 26 permits an order striking out a pleading in which no reasonable cause of action or defence is disclosed or where the pleading has a tendency to cause prejudice, embarrassment or delay in the proceeding or is otherwise an abuse of the process of the court.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The court's powers under Pt 15 r 26 are limited generally, but not exclusively, to the way in which the pleading has been framed. Under Pt 13 r 5, the court may go beyond the pleading and inquire into the actual facts of the case: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1935"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000082" spanref="cr000082-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="52"/><ci:page num="713"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000083" spanref="cr000083-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALJR"/><ci:volume num="9"/><ci:page num="127"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Cox v Journeaux (No 2)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000082-001" status="unval">(1935) 52 CLR 713</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000083-002" status="unval">9 ALJR 127</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1167" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. The power given by the latter is thus much wider than that given by the former.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Both rules reflect the inherent jurisdiction of the court to deal with the abuse of its process: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1889"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000084" spanref="cr000084-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="AppCas"/><ci:volume num="14"/><ci:page num="665"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000084" spanref="cr000084-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="668" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Reichel v Magrath</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000084-001" status="unval">(1889) 14 App Cas 665</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000084-002" status="unval">at 668</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="5204" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Under that inherent jurisdiction &#x2014; although now more properly under Pt 13 r 5 &#x2014; there is power to stay an action which, although properly pleaded, is bound to fail. Such an action may be called either vexatious or an abuse of process.</text></p>
<p>
<text>One such case would be where the legislature has provided an absolute defence which, on the facts pleaded in the statement of claim, must be applied so that there is no issue to be tried &#x2014; for example, the defences afforded by the Defamation Act 1974, Pt III Div 3 (&#x201c;Absolute Privilege&#x201d;).</text></p>
<p>
<text>Another such case would be where a second action was brought seeking to litigate an identical issue to that already decided against the plaintiff, so that a defence of <emph typestyle="it">res judicata</emph> must succeed: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1890"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000085" spanref="cr000085-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QBD"/><ci:volume num="25"/><ci:page num="1"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000085" spanref="cr000085-002"><ci:pinpoint num="9" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000085" spanref="cr000085-003"><ci:pinpoint num="10" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000085" spanref="cr000085-004" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="13" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">MacDougall v Knight</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000085-001" status="unval">(1890) 25 QBD 1</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000085-002">at 9,</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000085-003">10,</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000085-004" status="unval">13</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="12286" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Such cases are very rare; the genus of which they are but species is aptly named an abuse of the court's process, for relief will not be given in such cases unless the claim or defence being dismissed or struck out under such power amounts to an improper use of the machinery of the court: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1882"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000086" spanref="cr000086-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ChD"/><ci:volume num="22"/><ci:page num="397"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000086" spanref="cr000086-002"><ci:pinpoint num="399" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000086" spanref="cr000086-003"><ci:pinpoint num="407" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000086" spanref="cr000086-004" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="408" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">McHenry v Lewis</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000086-001" status="unval">(1882) 22 Ch D 397</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000086-002">at 399,</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000086-003">407,</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000086-004" status="unval">408</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="11443" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1886"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000087" spanref="cr000087-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="PD"/><ci:volume num="11"/><ci:page num="59"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000087" spanref="cr000087-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="63" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Willis v Earl Beaucham</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000087-001" status="unval">(1886) 11 PD 59</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000087-002" status="unval">at 63</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="36512" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; cf <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000088" spanref="cr000088-001"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1977"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="566"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000089" spanref="cr000089-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WLR"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1977"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="478"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000089" spanref="cr000089-003" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="489" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Goldsmith v Sperrings Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000088-001">[1977] 2 All ER 566</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000089-002" status="unval">[1977] 1 WLR 478</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000089-003" status="unval">at 489&#x2013;90</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="20069" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (the dissenting judgment of Lord Denning MR).</text></p>
<p>
<text>The present cannot be said to be such a case.</text></p>
<p>
<text>It is, however, urged on behalf of the cross-defendants that the provision, made in each of Pt 13 r 5 and Pt 15 r 26, that the court may receive evidence on the hearing of an application for the exercise of the powers they give leads to the conclusion that the first if not both of those rules was intended to permit the summary disposal of proceedings where the court is satisfied that the defendant has a good defence of the merits.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The cross-defendants seek to equate Pt 13 r 5 to RSC O 14(A) r 1 in Victoria, which gives that court the power to enter judgment for the defendant where he has &#x201c;a good defence on the merits&#x201d;. Even under such a rule, which appears to be peculiar to that State, this exercise of the power is reserved for &#x201c;actions that are absolutely hopeless&#x201d;: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1949"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000090" spanref="cr000090-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="78"/><ci:page num="62"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000090" spanref="cr000090-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="90" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000091" spanref="cr000091-003" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1949"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="333"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000092" spanref="cr000092-004"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC4900050"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Dey v Victorian Railway Cmrs</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000090-001" status="unval">(1949) 78 CLR 62</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000090-002" status="unval">at 90</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000091-003" status="unval">[1949] ALR 333</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000092-004"> BC4900050</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1020" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
<p>
<text>I do not think that Pt 13 r 5 can be interpreted in the way sought by the cross-defendants.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Evidence is relevant to Pt 15 r 26 in order to demonstrate the fault in the pleading &#x2014; for example, to show that a plaintiff in defamation has failed to plead the matter complained of in its proper context so as to produce a variance between what is pleaded and what must be proved to have been published: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1872"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000093" spanref="cr000093-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="LR4PC"/><ci:page num="287"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000093" spanref="cr000093-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="296" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Rainy v Bravo</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000093-001" status="unval">(1872) LR 4 PC 287</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000093-002" status="unval">at 296&#x2013;7</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1968"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000094" spanref="cr000094-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNPt1NSW"/><ci:volume num="88"/><ci:page num="146"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000094" spanref="cr000094-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="149" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Dougherty v Nationwide News Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000094-001" status="unval">(1968) 88 WN (Pt 1) (NSW) 146</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000094-002" status="unval">at 149&#x2013;51</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="82891" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. In this way, the application differs from the old procedure on demurrer, in which only the facts pleaded could be examined: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1919"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000095" spanref="cr000095-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="27"/><ci:page num="113"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000095" spanref="cr000095-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="118" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000096" spanref="cr000096-003" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="26"/><ci:page num="76"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Lubrano v Gollin &amp; Co Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000095-001" status="unval">(1919) 27 CLR 113</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000095-002" status="unval">at 118</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000096-003" status="unval">26 ALR 76</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="63575" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; GRC O XXIII r 3.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Evidence is relevant to Pt 13 r 5 in order to demonstrate that the facts, rather than the pleading, do not disclose a cause of action or a defence. Such evidence was admissible under the inherent jurisdiction: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000097" spanref="cr000097-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="Ch"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1893"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="545"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000097" spanref="cr000097-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="554" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Willis v Earl Howe</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000097-001" status="unval">[1893] 2 Ch 545</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000097-002" status="unval">at 554</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="79718" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; the rule merely reflects that practice&#x2026;</text></p>
<p>
<text>In general, Pt 13 r 5 is concerned more with the weakness of the plaintiff's case than with the strength of the defendant's case. The latter may be the basis of an application under Pt 13 r 5 only where to permit the action to go to trial constitutes an abuse of the process of the court. The present case is not one of the very rare cases in which such an abuse is apparent.</text></p>
<p>
<text>There are other reasons why an application for summary judgment would not be appropriate in this case.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The remedy afforded by Pt 13 r 5 is discretionary. Where part of a claim or cross-claim must in any event proceed to trial, the application for summary judgment on the other part would, in my view, have to show an exceedingly strong case why the whole case should not go to trial.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The need in a case such as this for interrogatories and discovery is another reason why the exercise of the summary jurisdiction of the court would be refused. It was argued on behalf of the cross-defendants that they would be available for cross-examination, and that the availability of such processes as the issue of subpoenas would make up for the lack of interrogatories and discovery.</text></p>
<p>
<text>I do not think that cross-examination is in any sense equivalent to interrogatories. A party answering interrogatories is bound to answer them not only from his own knowledge but also from the knowledge of his servants or agents: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1883"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000098" spanref="cr000098-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="AppCas"/><ci:volume num="9"/><ci:page num="92"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000098" spanref="cr000098-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="91" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Lyell v Kennedy (No 2)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000098-001" status="unval">(1883) 9 App Cas 92</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000098-002" status="unval">at 91</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000099" spanref="cr000099-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="VLR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1953"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="468"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000099" spanref="cr000099-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="472" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Hawkes v Schubach</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000099-001" status="unval">[1953] VLR 468</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000099-002" status="unval">at 472</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="27254" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000100" spanref="cr000100-001"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1974"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="77"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000100" spanref="cr000100-002"><ci:pinpoint num="80" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Adams v Dickeson</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000100-001">[1974] VR 77</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000100-002">at 80</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="93662" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; and even from servants and agents no longer in his employ: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1978"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000101" spanref="cr000101-001"><ci:reporter value="ACTR"/><ci:volume num="20"/><ci:page num="23"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000101" spanref="cr000101-002"><ci:pinpoint num="27" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Derham v AMEV Life Insurance Co Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000101-001">(1978) 20 ACTR 23</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000101-002">at 27</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="1294" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. No such obligation is placed upon a party being cross-examined. Nor can a subpoena be used as a substitute for discovery: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1938"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000102" spanref="cr000102-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="SRNSW"/><ci:volume num="38"/><ci:page num="564"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000102" spanref="cr000102-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="574" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000103" spanref="cr000103-003" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNNSW"/><ci:volume num="55"/><ci:page num="215"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Commissioner for Railways v Small</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000102-001" status="unval">(1938) 38 SR (NSW) 564</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000102-002" status="unval">at 574</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000103-003" status="unval">55 WN (NSW) 215</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="3681" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
<p>
<text>In these circumstances, an application for summary judgment in the present case would, in my view, be bound to fail.</text></p>
<p>
<text>Finally, in the event that I refused any other relief, the cross defendants sought a separate trial of the cross claim against them. They pointed, with some justification, to the narrowness of the issues with which they are concerned by comparison with those between the other parties to the proceedings, and to the costs they would unnecessarily have to incur by being present during a trial of all the issues together.</text></p>
<p>
<text>If the cross claim is not to be dismissed, either struck out or by summary judgment, the cross defendants say they want to have the cross claim against them disposed of prior to the trial of the other issues. The bank does not object to the grant of a separate trial, but does object to it being held in circumstances whereby the cross defendants are not bound by the findings of fact in the main action.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The principal object of what used to be called the third party procedure is to ensure that the third party is so bound: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000104" spanref="cr000104-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="KB"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1923"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="221"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000104" spanref="cr000104-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="224" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000105" spanref="cr000105-003" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="AllERRep"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1922"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="279"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Barclays Bank v Tom</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000104-001" status="unval">[1923] 1 KB 221</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000104-002" status="unval">at 224</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000105-003" status="unval">[1922] All ER Rep 279</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="31306" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. A separate trial, to comply with that object, would have to take place after the trial of the main action. And the cross defendants would have to agree to be bound by the findings in the earlier trial. A separate trial of the cross claim before the trial of the main action would, in my view, prejudice the bank, and I would not be prepared to grant it on that basis.</text></p></case:judgmentbody></case:judgment>
